1.1- Flipping coins!

The setup

As stated in the exercise, we will be playing as the professor of a class of n=150n=150 students. Out of these nn students we know that there are exactly kk non-honest students, leaving (nk)(nk) honest ones. It will be our job to tell them apart, by flipping coins!

We know that: * the (nk)(nk) honest students will use a fair coin, therefore the probability of a success (lets say, getting heads) is the same as getting tails, p=0.5p=0.5. * the kk cheaters will use (of course) a trick coin, of a given probability chosen arbitrarily only constrained in being greater that 0.50.5, hence q>pq>p.

Also, to better tell them apart, we are constrained with letting them throw their respective coins NN times, again chosen arbitrarily.

A first look at our data

By the setup we can already setup two random variables, which each assume values from repeated Bernoulli trials and counting the number of successes.

Let us write then:

XHBinom(N,p)XHBinom(N,p) H[1,(nk)]H[1,(nk)]
XLBinom(N,q)XLBinom(N,q) L[1,k]L[1,k]

First, we have to set the various variables!

N = 100  # Number of throws         - It's FIXED but variable, we are the prof afterall
n = 150  # Total number of students
k = 70   # liars
(n - k)  # The remaining honest ones 
## [1] 80
p = 0.5 
q = 0.65

Let us take a look at the two distribution! We expect them to follow two Binomials, each centered in NpNp and NqNq respectively.

Decisional functions!

According to the setup, we have to make them throw coins as long as it is necessary, therefore we have to come up with a decision rule to evaluate the result of the tosses. The first one is given to us by example: thresholding.

We will need a threshold parameter, namely to check the proportion of heads (which we identify as a success). Its simple:

# Set the threshold theta
decision_rule = function(throws_vec, theta, N){ 
  is_liar = (throws_vec) > (N * theta)
  return (is_liar) # ... by our decision rule
}

To put it simply: if the number of successes (heads) is above NN then we classify that person as a liar. Seems faulty, lets see if this statement has any ground.

A first simulation

We want to discover, for the given setup, what would be the results - meaning what quantities of true positive (TP), true negative (TN), false positive (FP), false negative (FN) we get for the given parameters and decision rule.

Side note : we will introduce a score function for our decision rule later on.

First off, lets set the simulation size. We found the value below to be acceptable, though if you want more stable results just increase it by one or more orders of magnitude. This last statement is in accordance to the assumption that asymptotically a sample quantity of interest better approximates the underlying population quantity of interest - namely the true/negative rates.

Let us start:

M = 1e2 # 1000, good enough!

# In our experiment we vary the thetas
num_thetas = 100 # So decide how many of them we want to test
theta_variations = seq(0.5, 1, length.out = num_thetas) # And set the threshold vector

Plus, we will analyze some additional scores, namely accuracy, precision, recall and f-1 Score. We should remember they are derived from the TP,TN,FP,FNTP,TN,FP,FN, but theyre a low hanging fruit, so why not include them!

rates = matrix(data = NA, nrow = num_thetas, ncol = 4) # Matrix where we'll register the TPR, FPR, TNR, FNR
scores = matrix(data = NA, nrow = num_thetas, ncol = 4)# Here we'll store accuracy, precision, recall, f1

for(idx in 1:num_thetas){
  
  theta = theta_variations[idx]
  rates_sim = matrix(data = NA, nrow = M, ncol = 4)
  scores_sim = matrix(data = NA, nrow = M, ncol = 4)
  
  for(m in 1:M){
    
    # Simulate the throws!
    honest_throws = rbinom(n = (n - k), size = N, prob = p)
    liar_throws = rbinom(n = k, size = N, prob = q)
    
    # The 1 * Boolean evaluates to an integer, which in our mind is easier 
    # to work with. Just a matter of preference :)
    classification_H = 1 * decision_rule(honest_throws, theta, N)
    classification_L = 1 * decision_rule(liar_throws, theta, N)
    
    # false positive -> (the student is apparently a liar | the student is actually honest)
    # false negative -> (the student is apparently honest | the student is actually a liar)
    
    tp = sum(classification_H == 0) # In the Honest students vector, which were classified as NOT LIAR? (0)
    fp = sum(classification_H == 1)
    tn = sum(classification_L == 1)
    fn = sum(classification_L == 0)
      
    tp_rate = tp / (n) # Calculate the rates wrt the population
    fp_rate = fp / (n) # for all of the various scores
    tn_rate = tn / (n) 
    fn_rate = fn / (n)
    
    
    # The low-hanging fruits. Why not!
    accuracy = (tn + tp)/n
    precision = tp / (tp + fp)
    recall = tp / (tp + fn)
    f1 = 2 * (precision * recall)/(precision + recall)
    
    rates_sim[m,] =  c(tp_rate, tn_rate, fp_rate, fn_rate)
    scores_sim[m, ] =c(accuracy, precision, recall, f1)   
  }
  
  
  # Each row is a different theta, in the columns their "performance"
  tp_rates_mean = mean(rates_sim[,1])
  tn_rates_mean = mean(rates_sim[,2])
  fp_rates_mean = mean(rates_sim[,3])
  fn_rates_mean = mean(rates_sim[,4])
  
  accuracy_mean = mean(scores_sim[,1])
  precision_mean = mean(scores_sim[,2])
  recall_mean = mean(scores_sim[,3])
  f1_mean = mean(scores_sim[,4])
  
  # Save everything into a matrix. Informally, we shall treat it as a table.
  rates[idx, ]  = c(tp_rates_mean, tn_rates_mean, fp_rates_mean, fn_rates_mean)
  scores[idx, ] = c(accuracy_mean, precision_mean, recall_mean, f1_mean)   
}

Lets see how the different theta did.

Optimizing. We want the best performance!

Lets take a step back first.

By the setup of the exercise, we do not have any real hard constraints which may indicate what could be better alternative in our decision process: - is it better to have more false positive or false negatives?, which translates to who do we want to penalize more, the honest ones or the liars?

We could be erring on the side of caution and implement a softer decisional threshold that allows more liars to be saved (and consequently the honest ones). Whats the softer constraint? A higher threshold - which lowers the false negative rate. What about a lower threshold? It would increase the false positives but would also be unfair to the honest student, but it would catch more cheaters.

Hint: its a tradeoff

We have the ability to choose which way to go, including what metric to choose to make our decision.

Choosing and - part 1.

In the exercise we need to set two levels, namely and to be our desired false positive and false negative rates respectively. In our head we like to imagine it as the gold standard given by the Supreme Commission for Decision Making of Sapienza University to us, the professor, and we need to be able to get closer to it as possible. Of course a 0 for both would be perfect, but were afraid theres a flaw since the beginning. We will do our best!

But how?

Extending for time elapsed

In the second part of the exercise (1.2) we had to introduce time as a penalizing factor in our scores. So suppose we introduce a time constraint. How can we enforce it? Again, multiple ways of doing it.

A fun experiment we did was creating what we called the redemption function. Heres the code:

decision_function_v1 = function(tosses_ratio, theta = 0.59){
  is_liar = 1 * (tosses_ratio >= theta)
  return (is_liar)
}

tp_v1 = sum(decision_function_v1(honest_throws) == 0)/n
tn_v1 = sum(decision_function_v1(liar_throws) == 1)/n
fp_v1 = sum(decision_function_v1(honest_throws) == 1)/n
fn_v1 = sum(decision_function_v1(liar_throws) == 0)/n



theta1 = 0.55 # Below this? All good!
theta2 = 0.60 # Below this? Check again with 10 throws..
theta3 = 0.63 # WHAT? Below this? 5 more chance.
theta4 = 0.67 # You get 1 more chance.
              # After 0.8 ratio you're out, liar....

N = 10 # The starting number of tosses per student. 30 seconds. 
tau = 3  # seconds per throw

honest_throws = rbinom(n-k, size = N, prob = p)
honest_throws = cbind(honest_throws, honest_throws * tau)

liar_throws = rbinom(k, size = N, prob = q)
liar_throws = cbind(liar_throws, liar_throws * tau)


decision_function_v2 = function(results, prob){
  
  throws = results[,1]
  times = results[,2]
  is_liar = rep(NA, length(throws))
  
  alpha1 = theta1 * N # Set 4 
  alpha2 = theta2 * N # thresholds
  alpha3 = theta3 * N # for the 
  alpha4 = theta4 * N # experiment
  
  
  for(idx in 1:length(throws)){
    if(throws[idx] <= alpha1){
      is_liar[idx] = 0
    } else if(throws[idx] > alpha1 & throws[idx] <= alpha2){
      times[idx] = times[idx] + (tau * 10) # Time spent tossing 10 coins
      is_liar[idx] = decision_function_v1(rbinom(1, size = 10, prob = prob)/10, theta = 0.5)
    } else if(throws[idx] > alpha2 & throws[idx] <= alpha3){
      times[idx] = times[idx] + (tau * 5)  # Time spent tossing 5 coins 
      is_liar[idx] = decision_function_v1(rbinom(1, size = 5, prob = prob)/5, theta = 0.5)
    } else if (throws[idx] > alpha1 & throws[idx] <= alpha2){
      times[idx] = times[idx] + (tau * 1)  # Time spent tossing 1 coin.
      is_liar[idx] = decision_function_v1(rbinom(1, size = 1, prob = prob), theta = 0.5)
    } else {
      is_liar[idx] = 1
    }
  }
  
  return(cbind(throws, times, is_liar))
}



honest_results = decision_function_v2(honest_throws, prob = p)
liar_results = decision_function_v2(liar_throws, prob = q)

hist(honest_results[,2], col = "green", xlab = "Time spent throwing coins", prob = F, main = "An alternative using tau- time elapsed.")

2.1 Estimation of the quantile

To pick an implementation of f h(.)f^h(.) we first need to have a look into our distribution.

We know that X has a Beta(,) distribution and we consider FX(.)FX(.) as the true population model.

# Set the seed
set.seed(1234) 

#Set up
N_samples = 1000 

# Pick two different (alpha, beta) pairs
alpha_1 <- 1.5
beta_1 <- 3.5

# Generate random samples from a beta distribution - True scenario
true_population = rbeta(N_samples, shape1 = alpha_1, shape2 = beta_1)

After picking = 1.5 and = 3.5, we plot the PDF fX(.)fX(.) of the true population and the histograms.

Now we consider FY(.)FY(.) as an approximation to FX(.)FX(.) and the Kernel Density Estimator (KDE) f h(.)f^h(.) for which we need to choose a bandwith h > 0.

# Approximate scenario 
alpha_2 <- 2 
beta_2 <- 4.5

approx_population = rbeta(N_samples, shape1 = alpha_2, shape2 = beta_2)

After setting h = 0.3 we implement the Epanechnikov Kernel Density Estimator with the density() function, and we plot it:

# Set the bandwidth for the kernel density estimator
h = 0.3 # h has to be more than zero

KDE = density(approx_population, bw = h, kernel = "epanechnikov")
plot(KDE, main = "Kernel Density Estimator [Epanechnikov]", lwd = 2.5, col = "darkred")

Now we compute the approximated PDF and CDF:

 approx_pdf <- approxfun(KDE$x, KDE$y, method = 'linear', yleft = 0, yright = 0)
 
 approx_cdf <- function(x, approx_pdf) {
  integrate(approx_pdf, -Inf, x)$value
}

And the estimation F1^h(.)F1^h(.) of the quantile using the Epanechnikov-Kernel:

compute_approx_quantile_epan_kernel <- function(x, h, z){
  KDE = density(x, bw = h, kernel = "epanechnikov")
  
  # Compute the approximate CDF values for each x
  x_values <- seq(min(KDE$x), max(KDE$x), length.out = length(KDE$x))
  cdf_values <- sapply(x_values, function(x) approx_cdf(x, approx_pdf))
  
  # Linear interpolation is performed to obtain a function, not just a set of points
  approx_pdf <- approxfun(KDE$x, KDE$y, method = 'linear', yleft = 0, yright = 0)
  
  # We are looking for the point where approx_cdf(x, approx_pdf) - z is zero, 
  # and this point is approximately our desired quantile
  approx_quantile <- uniroot(function(x) approx_cdf(x, approx_pdf) - z, c(min(KDE$x), max(KDE$x)))$root
  return(list(x_values = x_values, cdf_values = cdf_values, approx_quantile = approx_quantile))
}

2.2 Compute the Wasserstein-Distance

Compute Wasserstein-Distance, looking for the largest bandwidth h such that:

WL1,1(f,fh^)=(10|F1(z)F1h^(z)|dz)WL1,1(f,fh^)=(01|F1(z)Fh1^(z)|dz)
Lets compute the first element, F1(z)F1(z)

compute_true_quantile <- function(z){
  qbeta(z, alpha_1, beta_1)
}

that we will use to compute the Wasserstein-Distance formula implemented by hand:

wass_distance <- function(z, approx_quantile) {
  return(integrate(function(z) abs(compute_true_quantile(z) - approx_quantile), 0, 1)$value)
}

Now lets search, through a series of plots, for the largest bandwidth h in a range of values that we set from 0.05 to 1.5. These plots show both the cdf with the true and estimated quantile and also the correspondent h and Wasserstein-Distance value on the top of the graph:

compute_largest_bandwidth_h <- function(z, epsilon){
  max_h <- NULL  
  x_values <- seq(min(approx_population), max(approx_population), length.out = 100)
  
  for (h_i in h){
    result <- compute_approx_quantile_epan_kernel(approx_population, h_i, z)
    x_values <- result$x_values
    cdf_values <- result$cdf_values
    approx_quantile <- result$approx_quantile
    wass_distance_value <- wass_distance(z, approx_quantile)

    # Visualization
    print(paste("h_i:", h_i, "approx_quantile:", round(approx_quantile,4), 
                "true_quantile:", round(compute_true_quantile(z), 4)))
    print(paste("Wasserstein-Distance:", round(wass_distance_value, 4)))
    
    plot_distance(x_values, cdf_values, compute_true_quantile(z), approx_quantile, h_i, wass_distance_value)
    
    if (wass_distance_value <= epsilon) {
        max_h <- h_i
    } 
    else{
      break
    }
  }
    return(max_h)
}

We know that a small bandwidth h leads to undersmoothing and a large bandwidth leads to oversmoothing, and we also know that the smaller the the more accurate the distance, but it may take more time computationally.

From the 3 sets of simulations we made (for = 0.15, = 0.2, and = 0.5) we can see that the more we increase the more the distance and the bandwidth h increase. This means that the distance measure will become less sensitive to small differences in the distribution, effectively ignoring small fluctuations. Also, we can observe that for values of < 0.2, the distance is actually > so that cases are not valid. Then we can assert that this distance actually has a lower bound.

If we are looking for the largest bandwidth h such that

WL1,1(f,fh^)=(10|F1(z)F1h^(z)|dz)WL1,1(f,fh^)=(01|F1(z)Fh1^(z)|dz)
from the simulation we made, we can conclude that to achieve this result we have to decrease the bandwidth.

Decreasing h and consequentially getting a smaller , also leads to a smaller distance. This means that the two quantiles we are comparing, the one from the true population and the approximate one, are almost the same.
